<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:110px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Rawandi.jpg" class="image" title="Ibn Al-Rawandi"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/55/Rawandi.jpg" width="108" height="150" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Rawandi.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<b>Ibn Al-Rawandi</b></div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Ibn al-Rawandi</b> (<a href="/wiki/827" title="827">827</a> – <a href="/wiki/911" title="911">911</a>)<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> was an early skeptic of <a href="/wiki/Islam" title="Islam">Islam</a> and a critic of <a href="/wiki/Religion" title="Religion">religion</a> in general. In his early days he was a <a href="/wiki/Mutazilite" title="Mutazilite" class="mw-redirect">Mutazilite</a> scholar but after rejecting the Mutazilte doctrine he adhered <a href="/wiki/Shia" title="Shia" class="mw-redirect">Shia</a> Islam for a brief period of time and later became a <a href="/wiki/Freethinker" title="Freethinker" class="mw-redirect">freethinker</a> who repudiated Islam and revealed religion<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup>.Though none of his works survived his opinions had been preserved through his critics and the surviving books that answered him. The book with the most preserved fragments through an <a href="/wiki/Ismaili" title="Ismaili" class="mw-redirect">Ismaili</a> book refuting Al-Rawandi's ideology , is the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Kitab_al-Zumurrud&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Kitab al-Zumurrud (page does not exist)">Kitab al-Zumurrud</a> (The Book of the Emerald).</p>
